# Project Overview {#project-overview}

## Top Line Overview {#top-line-overview}

In this project, you will be responsible for developing runtime environments for an LLM agent to solve SWE problems for specific public GitHub repos. You will be writing Dockerfiles and bash scripts to be executed in the docker container that install all testing / development dependencies for that repo and then execute the test suite within the container. You will also write a Python string parsing script to parse the raw test outputs into a structured JSON.

The objective is to replicate the repo’s development environment in the container and successfully execute most/all of the test suite. To assist you, we provide access to Cursor, an LLM coding assistant as well as file templates (including pre-written Cursor prompts) for building these environments. Cursor is meant to be an assistant and you are not required to use it.

You are required to use the templates provided and are strongly encouraged to familiarise yourself with the LLM prompts as instructions for producing each deliverable file. [SWEAP Template for JavaScript and TS v6](https://drive.google.com/file/d/13XIGnQw8TVUA0KDZ4tG4cC7vuYGyn1x-/view?usp=sharing) \- [SWEAP Template for Python v10](https://drive.google.com/file/d/1Z6xCW84jnvrw_FIFpznYSDmL0BsB54ee/view?usp=sharing) \-  [SWEAP Template for GO v3](https://drive.google.com/file/d/1jFJJE1VxrPfWgy14ZyMTIx029G4YuQ-7/view?usp=sharing)

## Project Background {#project-background}

The objective of Project Hyperion is to compile a new dataset of 5k [SWE-Bench](https://www.swebench.com/) style problems. These problems are used to assess the ability of LLM SWE agents to work in large code bases and solve the types of problems traditionally encountered by software developers working in these code bases. 

To complete the assessment, agents are given a codebase (a repository) and a description of an issue to be solved. The solution developed by the LLM is then compared against the actual solution implemented (i.e., the golden patch; a real GitHub PR responding to the issue) and tested using the repository’s test suite and any tests implemented as part of the golden patch.

See the [glossary](#heading=h.wcmshua43d3s) for definitions of different components of a SWE-Bench problem.

## Project Deliverables {#project-deliverables}

The deliverable outputs of your work will be 5 files:

* **Dockerfile \-** A standard Dockerfile containing instructions to select a base image, install git, clone the repository, install system packages, and setup build tools  
* **build.sh \-** A build script executed in the Dockerfile to install project dependencies, configure environment variables, and build the repo  
* **run.sh \-** A script to execute the test suite of the repository after it has been built  
* **parsing.py \-** A python utility for parsing the output of the repository test suite  
* **test\_results.json** \- A json file that contains the output of the tests.

**To be a valid solution, an environment must execute and most/pass all tests in a repository’s test suite.** 

Skipped tests and expected failure (XFAIL) tests are allowed.

# Cursor Overview {#cursor-overview}

## Workflow and Cursor Overview {#workflow-and-cursor-overview}

**![][image2]**

To construct the environments, you will use Cursor, an AI-powered text editor that you will guide to analyze the repository and build the necessary development environment. Cursor functions similarly to VS Code but with AI compatibility. The text editor will handle most of the code creation, while your job is to guide it in taking the correct actions and get it back on track when it makes mistakes.

The primary feature of Cursor that we will be using is the Chat and Composer agents. This agent has access to the entire workspace directory, including your terminal. It can perform create, read, update, and delete (CRUD) operations on any files within its scope in the workspace. However, any updates or deletions it suggests will not be applied until you either fully or partially accept them. You also have the option to decline changes entirely, manually update them yourself, or nudge the agent to fix the issue.  

Keep in mind that the agent will not have any scope of which GitHub repo you are working on. So please provide that at the very beginning of your conversation.

## **Detailed Instructions** {#detailed-instructions}

**Note that all instructions given in this document are done on MacOS. Exact terminal commands may differ depending on your operating system.**

The following is a walkthrough of how to complete an environment. This walkthrough will leverage the repository “Mkdocs” (a Python tool for converting files and office documents to Markdown). You can find finalized solutions for the Requests repository in the [Sample Solutions](?tab=t.c0u6r413cpb3) tab.

1. ### Claim New Task on the Claims Google Sheet {#claim-new-task-on-the-claims-google-sheet}

**Objective \-** Understand the structure of a repository and approximately what is needed to build a development environment.

Select a task from the [\[External\] Attempts sheet - Hyperion Env Building ](https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1BrygHc5F8PqLds0YOOf1W1NbPggkpMLxcggDtXlQjY8/edit?gid=331974809#gid=331974809). Populate the following columns in the worksheet:

1. Attempter \- Your email  
2. Status \- Mark ‘In Progress’  
3. Claimed at \- The Current time and date

![][image5]

When you open the repository in Outlier, you will be given a repository to work with in the ‘Instructions’ section. Open the repository through the link in this section and familiarize yourself with the contents. You can also view the repository using the ‘Repository Link’ column in the Google Sheets.

Your goal is to understand the structure of the repository and how to build a development environment for building in the repository.![][image6]Some key areas of focus that you will find helpful are:

* The README file  
* Any requirements or other dependency list files (e.g., requirements.txt)  
* Contributors guides and other files related to helping repository contributors get started  
* Makefiles  
* Test folders  
* Testing configuration files (e.g., pyproject.toml)

See the [Common Key Files](?tab=t.vkjftgd0l7gm) tab for more information on helpful files to familiarize yourself with.

### **IMPORTANT SUBSTEP** {#important-substep}

When you are familiarizing yourself with the repository, look out for the following forms of illegal information in the repository:

* Personally Identifiable Information (e.g., personal names and other details that could identify someone)  
* Company logos  
* Pictures of peoples faces  
* Trademarks

If you identify any of these things, check the box for “Illegal information” in the Outlier form and describe what illegal information is present and where in the repository. This will be used by the Outlier team to scrub it from our final dataset.

![][image7]

2. ### Setup Your Directory and Clone Your Assigned GitHub Repository {#setup-your-directory-and-clone-your-assigned-github-repository}

**Objective \-** Create an environment in Cursor to work on the problem

After you have familiarized yourself with the repository, we need to create a template directory in Cursor to do so. To do this, download the following zip file and unzip it into a working directory:  [SWEAP Template for JavaScript and TS v6](https://drive.google.com/file/d/13XIGnQw8TVUA0KDZ4tG4cC7vuYGyn1x-/view?usp=sharing) \- [SWEAP Template for Python v10](https://drive.google.com/file/d/1Z6xCW84jnvrw_FIFpznYSDmL0BsB54ee/view?usp=sharing) \-  [SWEAP Template for GO v3](https://drive.google.com/file/d/1jFJJE1VxrPfWgy14ZyMTIx029G4YuQ-7/view?usp=sharing)\-  (select the template based on the programming language)

3. ### Agent Context Gathering {#agent-context-gathering}

**Objective \-** Guide the agent to gather as much context about the repository and its files as is needed for it to write a Dockerfile and set up a development and testing environment for the repository.

Before you can ask the agent to gather information, you need to know what information needs to be gathered first. The README.md file provided gives you a good idea of what to look for. There is also a [Common Key Files](?tab=t.vkjftgd0l7gm) tab for common files that you should guide the agent to read. **Note that this list is non-exhaustive** and you must use your best judgment in determining what the agent needs to read in a given repository.

Now that you have familiarized yourself with the repository, it is time to familiarize the agent with the repository. *Before you create any prompts in the agent, make sure you have cloned the repo to the workspace in a directory called ‘app’.* Once you have Cursor opened, use the command  `Ctrl + I` on Windows or `CMD + I` on Mac to open the **chat agent**. Inside that chatbox is where you are going to start the conversation with the agent.

The start of your conversation with the agent should ask it to follow the instructions in the s1\_localization.txt file and the GitHub repo.

**Example:**

```
Follow the instructions in @s1_localization.txt . Use the following files for context: @README.md @requirements.txt @tox.ini @setup.py @setup.cfg @CONTRIBUTING.md 
```

After it runs, read the output message and identify any additional files you may need to give it context for (based on its suggestions or your exploration of the repository).

4. ### Write the Dockerfile {#write-the-dockerfile}

**Objective \-** Write a working Dockerfile

After you read all the relevant context into the Dockerfile, it is time to move onto step 2\. Instruct the model to follow the instructions in `s2_dockerfile.txt`

```

Follow the instructions in @s2_dockerfile.txt . Propose edits to the  @Dockerfile, keeping in mind that the project dependencies and configuration will be in the @build.sh.

```

This will cause the system to propose edits to the existing Dockerfile which you can review and accept, reject, or edit. Do this to create your initial version of the Dockerfile.  
![][image10]  
![][image11]

**Key Sense Checks \- Avoid These Common Errors To Pass Verification**  
**Sense Check \#1:** Ensure the Dockerfile contains a clone to the GitHub repository, this step is sometimes ignored by the model.   
![][image12]

**Sense Check \#2:** Ensure the Dockerfile ends with the line \`ENTRYPOINT \[“/bin/bash”\]  
![][image13]

**Sense Check \#3: When writing the Dockerfile for non-Python projects (e.g., JavaScript, TypeScript), make sure to include the following required system dependencies (For JS/TS only use debian based images that has these dependencies):**

```
python3 \
python3-pip \
python3-setuptools \
python-is-python3 \
```

A complete example would look like this:

```
RUN apt-get update && apt-get install -y --no-install-recommends \
    git \
    make \
    llvm \
    clang \
    libelf-dev \
    gcc \
    iproute2 \
    pkg-config \
    python3 \
    python3-pip \
    python3-setuptools \
    python-is-python3 \
    binutils \
    build-essential \
    netcat-openbsd \
    sudo \
    ca-certificates \
    curl \
    bison \
    flex \
    && apt-get clean \
    && rm -rf /var/lib/apt/lists/*
```

**Sense Check \#4: do not create virtuals environments. Avoid using venv, uv, poetry, hatch, etc.** 

- If the repo forces you to use **tox** there is a specific configuration that needs to be used:

```
pip install tox tox-current-env
tox --current-env -e ...
```

5. ### Write the build.sh file to install project dependencies and build the environment {#write-the-build.sh-file-to-install-project-dependencies-and-build-the-environment}

Implement the build script in `/workspace/build.sh` to configure and build the repository. The script should:

* Install project dependencies.  
* Configure necessary environment variables.  
* Respect custom build scripts if present.  
* Handle any special cases discovered during analysis.

**Example prompt (if you haven't made any changes to the build.sh file):**

```
Follow the instructions in @s3_build_script.txt to propose edits to the build.sh file. 
```

**Example of `/build.sh` file:**

```
#!/bin/sh
# Common Setup, DO NOT MODIFY
cd /app
set -e

###############################################
# PROJECT DEPENDENCIES AND CONFIGURATION
###############################################
# TODO: Install project dependencies if needed based on relevant config/lock files in the repo.
# Note that we are developing the project, even if dependencies have been installed before, we need to install again to accommodate the changes we made.
pip install --no-cache-dir ".[dev]"

###############################################
# ENVIRONMENT VARIABLE CONFIGURATION
###############################################
# In this case, we don't need to configure environment variables.

###############################################
# BUILD
###############################################
echo "================= 0909 BUILD START 0909 ================="
# TODO: Build the project if needed. Note that we are developing the project and making changes to it, even if it has been build before, we need to build it again.
# No specific build command is needed for Loguru, as it is a library.
echo "================= 0909 BUILD END 0909 ================="



```

Once implemented, build the Docker image by executing:

```
docker build -t <image_name> .
```

**Example:**

```
docker build -t markitdown-v2 .
```

If errors occur, refine the build script as needed.

6. ### Write the run.sh file to execute the repo’s test suite **\[UPDATED 4/2\]** {#write-the-run.sh-file-to-execute-the-repo’s-test-suite-[updated-4/2]}

Implement the run script in `/workspace/run.sh` to configure and run tests. This script should:

* Configure the test framework for detailed output (e.g., `pytest -v`).  
* Enable individual test case status reporting.  
* Set up test discovery for quick feedback.  
* Log failures, stack traces, and skipped tests.

The run.sh file is divided into two sections, \`run\_all\_tests\` and \`run\_selected\_tests\`. These are the only two sections of the file that you need to configure.

Prompt the model to follow the steps in \`s4\_tests.txt\` to have it help you write these tests. For example:

```
Follow the instructions in @s4_tests.txt to update @run.sh to execute tests.
```

**Run All Tests**

In this section, you write a test command to run the full test suite of the repository. This is the same test command that instructions requested you to write before the April 2nd update.

**Example**

```
run_all_tests() {
  echo "Running all tests..."
  # Example: pytest tests/
  poetry run pytest tests/ \
    -v \
    --tb=short
}
```

**Testing**

Execute the following command to run all tests, store them to \`stdout.txt\` and \`stderr.txt\`, and verify that 95%+ of the tests pass:

```
docker run -v "$(pwd)":/workspace YOUR_IMAGE_NAME_HERE /workspace/run.sh >stdout.txt 2>stderr.txt

### EXAMPLE
docker run -v "$(pwd)":/workspace textualize_new /workspace/run.sh >stdout.txt 2>stderr.txt
```

**Run Selected Tests**

NOTE: THIS SECTION IS NEW WITH THE APRIL 2 UPDATE

In this section, you configure the run.sh file to take a command line argument listing specific tests or test files that you want to execute. The function should run tests but take as input the command line argument ”${test\_files\[@\]}”

**Example**

```
run_selected_tests() {
```

7. ### \[If needed\] Debug the Docker image so all tests pass {#[if-needed]-debug-the-docker-image-so-all-tests-pass}

**Objective \-** Validate that the Docker image builds and executes all tests properly.

In the previous step, when you ran the full test suite  (Run All Tests) using the following command:

```
docker run -v "$(pwd)":/workspace mkdocs-image /workspace/run.sh >stdout.txt 2>stderr.txt
```

The tests outputs were saved to the \`stdout.txt\` and \`stderr.txt\` files. Review the test outputs in this file. If they pass, great. Move onto the next step.

If not all tests pass, then you need to use Cursor to debug why the tests are failing, and update your files accordingly. 

**Reasons why your tests may be failing (in order of likelihood):**

1. **build.sh \-** You are missing project dependencies  
2. **run.sh \-** You are not executing the correct test suite  
3. **Dockerfile \-** You need to update your system dependencies or base image

Debug the failing tests by making updates the build.sh, run.sh, and Dockerfile. Rebuild the docker image and rerun your test suite until you get all tests to pass. Once all tests are passing, you can move onto the next step.

8. ### Write parsing.py {#write-parsing.py}

**Objective \-** Write a parsing script to convert the raw test suite execution output into a structured JSON

Once tests run, implement `/workspace/parsing.py` to process the test results. The parser should:

* Extract individual test case results.  
* Categorize them as **PASSED, FAILED, SKIPPED,** or **ERROR**.  
* Capture failure details and stack traces.  
* Generate a structured JSON report (`/workspace/test_results.json`).

9. ### Parse The Test Results {#parse-the-test-results}

**Objective \-** Test the parser.py function and successfully parse and analyze the repository test results from the Docker image. 

After writing parsing.py, getting all tests to pass, and writing the output of the test suite to stdout.txt, you can run the following command to execute the parsing.py script:

```

make test_parser
```

This will run the parser.py script which will (ideally) parse the output of the tests into a json file test\_results.json that contains the name and status of each test.

If your output runs successfully the first time, great\! Move onto task submission. Note that the following errors are common and requires debugging:

* No tests included in JSON  
* Not all tests included in JSON  
* Test names incorrect in JSON  
* Test status (e.g., pass/fail) incorrect in JSON  
* \[Similar to above\] \# of tests listed in JSON does not match with number of tests executed listed in stdout.txt

Closely inspect your stdout.txt, stderr.txt and test\_results.json to ensure that parsing is working properly and there are no errors\! All tests run and appearing in stdout.txt or stderr.txt should appear in test\_results.json.

If your parsing.py function does not function properly, then use the agent to edit the parser.py file until it corrects the errors and produces the correct output when you run \`make test\_parser\`. The agent will be able to read the contents of test\_results.json and will receive any error messages, so it should be able to debug the parsing.py file relatively efficiently.

Also, validate again using test\_results.json that no tests have the status of “FAILED”. If they do, then you will need to return to the Dockerfile debugging section and ask the agent to resolve any failed tests. 

Note that you can chat with the agent and suggest issues with the parsing.py file and ask it to correct them.
